Let $\mathcal T$ be an admissible $p$-adic formal scheme over $\Spf W$, and consider the sheaf of rings $\cO_{\mathcal T}[\![u]\!]$. ootnote{In the context of \Cref{Example:prisms}(2), the reader may take $\mathcal T = \Spf R_0$ as a working example in this subsection.} We say $\mathcal T$ is regular if every local ring is regular. In this section we prove the following:  egin{proposition}\label{prop:blow-up to resolve} Let $\mathcal T$ be a regular 2-dimensional $p$-adic formal scheme over $\Spf W$ and $E$ a finitely generated $\cO_{\mathcal T}[\![u]\!]$-module. Then there is a sequence \[ \mathcal T'=\mathcal T_n	o\cdots 	o\mathcal T_1=\mathcal T\] of formal admissible blow-ups at closed points, such that $(f[\![u]\!]^*E)^{\vee\vee}$ is locally free as an $\mathcal O_{\mathcal T} [\![u]\!]$-module, where $f: \mathcal T' ightarrow \mathcal T$ denotes the composition of sequence of maps above. \end{proposition} We begin with the following observation.  egin{lemma}\label{lem:vanishing}Let $\cO$ be a 3-dimensional regular local ring and $E$ a finitely generated reflexive $\cO$-module. Then $\Ext^i_\cO(E,\cO)=0$ for $i>1$. \end{lemma}  egin{proof} Every term in the double dual spectral sequence \[R\Hom_\cO(R\Hom_\cO(E,\cO),\cO)=E\] vanishes except $E^{\vee\vee}$, $\Ext^1_\cO(E^\vee,\cO)$, and $\Ext^3_\cO(\Ext^1_\cO(E,\cO),\cO)$. In particular, this implies that $\Ext^3_\cO(\Ext^i_\cO(E,\cO),\cO)=0$ for $i>1$, so $\Ext^i_\cO(E,\cO)=0$ by local duality. \end{proof} The main step of \Cref{prop:blow-up to resolve} is the following:  egin{lemma}\label{lem:strictly decreasing}Let $\cO$ be a 3-dimensional regular local ring and $E$ a finitely generated reflexive $\cO$-module which is not free. Let $f:X	o\Spec\cO$ be the blow-up along any regular curve. Then we have \[\ell(\sExt^1_{\cO_X}((f^*E)^\vee,\cO_X))<\ell(\Ext^1_\cO(E^\vee,\cO)),\] where $\ell $ denotes the length of ($\mathcal O$-)modules. \end{lemma}  egin{proof} 
oindent\emph{Step 1.} $E$ has a presentation of the form  egin{equation}\label{eq:present} egin{tikzcd}0\ar[r]&\cO^m\ar[r,"A"]&\cO^n\ar[r]& E\ar[r]& 0\end{tikzcd}.
otag\end{equation}  egin{proof} Consider any presentation  egin{equation}\label{eq:present} egin{tikzcd}\cO^m\ar[r,"A"]&\cO^n\ar[r]& E\ar[r]& 0\end{tikzcd}.
otag\end{equation} We claim that $N=\img(A)$ is free. Indeed, applying $RHom_\cO(-,\cO)$ to the sequence \[ egin{tikzcd}0\ar[r]&N\ar[r]&\cO^n\ar[r]& E\ar[r]& 0\end{tikzcd}\] and using \Cref{lem:vanishing}, we see that $\Ext^i_\cO(N,\cO)=0$ for $i>0$. \end{proof} 
oindent\emph{Step 2.} Let $M$ be any nonzero finitely-generated $\cO$-module supported on (some thickening of) the closed point $x$ of $\Spec\cO$. Then $L^if^*M=0$ for $i<-1$ and $H^0(\sExt_{\cO_X}^2(L^{-1}f^*M,\cO_X))
eq 0$.  egin{proof}First observe that the vanishing claim is true for $M=k(x)$ using the Koszul resolution. In general we may take a short exact sequence \[ egin{tikzcd} 0\ar[r]&M'\ar[r] &M\ar[r]&k(x)\ar[r]&0. \end{tikzcd}\] and the vanishing follows from the above observation by induction on $\ell(M)$. For the second claim, again observe that the claim is true for $M=k(x)$ since $L^{-1}f^*k(x)=\cO_C(-1)$ where $C=f^{-1}(x)\cong \P^1_{k(x)}$ and $\sExt^2_{\cO_X}(\cO_C(-1),\cO_X)=\cO_C$. In general, using the same sequence we have an exact sequence \[  egin{tikzcd} 0\ar[r]&L^{-1}f^*M'\ar[r]&L^{-1}f^*M \ar[r]& \cO_C(-1) \end{tikzcd} \] and the image of the rightmost map is therefore either 0 or $\cO_C(-a)$ for some $a\geq 1$. Thus by induction we may assume we are in the latter case. But then we have an inclusion \[ egin{tikzcd} 0\ar[r]&\cO_C(a-1)\cong\sExt^2_{\cO_X}(\cO_C(-a),\cO_X)\ar[r]& \sExt^2_{\cO_X}(L^{-1}f^*M,\cO_X) \end{tikzcd}\] whence the claim. \end{proof} Taking the dual of the presentation from Step 1 we have \[ egin{tikzcd} 0\ar[r]&E^\vee\ar[r]&\cO^n\ar[r,"A^*"]&\cO^m\ar[r]&\Ext^1_\cO(E,\cO)\ar[r]&0. \end{tikzcd}\] Let $F=\img(A^*)$ and $Q=\Ext^1_\cO(E,\cO)$. \vskip1em 
oindent\emph{Step 3.} We have $L^if^*F=0$ and $L^if^*(E^\vee)=0$ for $i<0$.  egin{proof}Pulling back the sequence \[ egin{tikzcd} 0\ar[r]&F\ar[r]&\cO^m\ar[r]& Q\ar[r]&0 \end{tikzcd}\] and using the vanishing in Step 2 implies the first claim. Pulling back \[ egin{tikzcd} 0\ar[r]&E^\vee\ar[r]&\cO^n\ar[r]& F\ar[r]&0 \end{tikzcd}\] and using the first claim implies the second. \end{proof} 
oindent\emph{Step 4.} There is a natural short exact sequence \[ egin{tikzcd} 0\ar[r]&f^*(E^\vee)\ar[r] &(f^*E)^\vee\ar[r]&L^{-1}f^*Q\ar[r]&0. \end{tikzcd}\]  egin{proof}Since $\cO_X$ is torsion-free, pulling back the presentation from Step 1 we have an exact sequence \[ egin{tikzcd} 0\ar[r]&\cO_X^m\ar[r,"f^*A"]&\cO_X^n\ar[r]&f^*E\ar[r]&0 \end{tikzcd}\] and therefore an exact seqeunce \[ egin{tikzcd} 0\ar[r]&(f^*E)^\vee\ar[r]&\cO_X^n\ar[r,"f^*A^*"]&\cO_X^m. \end{tikzcd}\] Now applying the previous step to the diagram with exact diagonals \[ egin{tikzcd}[/tikz/cells={/tikz/nodes={shape=asymmetrical rectangle,text width=1.5cm,text height=2ex,text depth=0.3ex,align=center}},row sep=tiny, column sep=tiny] {}&0\ar[dr]&{}&{}&{}&{}&{}\ {}&{}&L^{-1}f^*Q\ar[dr]&{}&0&{}&{}\ {}&{}&{}&f^*F\ar[ur]\ar[dr]&{}&{}&{}\ {}&{}&\cO_X^n\ar[ur]\ar[rr,"f^*A^*",swap]&{}&\cO_X^m\ar[rd]&{}&{}\ {}& f^*(E^\vee)\ar[ur]&{}&{}&{}&f^*Q\ar[rd]&{}\ L^{-1}f^*F\ar[ur]&{}&{}&{}&{}&{}&0 \end{tikzcd}\] yields the claim. \end{proof} 
oindent\emph{Step 5.} There is a natural short exact sequence \[ egin{tikzcd} 0\ar[r]&H^1(f^*(E^\vee)^\vee)\ar[r] &\Ext^1_{\cO}(E^\vee,\cO)\ar[r]&H^0(\sExt_{\cO_X}^1(f^*(E^\vee),\cO_X))\ar[r]&0. \end{tikzcd}\] In particular, $\ell(\sExt_{\cO_X}^1(f^*(E^\vee),\cO_X))\leq \ell(\Ext^1_\cO(E^\vee,\cO))$.  egin{proof}Use \[Rf_*(R\sHom_{\cO_X}(Lf^*(E^\vee),\cO_X))=R\Hom_\cO(E^\vee,Rf_*\cO_X)\] together with $Rf_*\cO_X=\cO$ and the vanishing of $L^{i}f^*(E^\vee)$ for $i<0$ from Step 3. \end{proof} 
oindent\emph{Step 6.} \[\ell(\sExt^1_{\cO_X}((f^*E)^\vee,\cO_X))\leq \ell(\Ext^1_\cO(E^\vee,\cO))-\ell(H^0(\sExt^2_{\cO_X}(L^{-1}f^*Q,\cO_X))).\]  egin{proof} Applying $R\Hom_{\cO_X}(-,\cO_X)$ to the sequence from Step 4 and using the vanishing from \Cref{lem:vanishing} we have an exact sequence \[ egin{tikzcd} 0\ar[r]&\sExt^1_{\cO_X}((f^*E)^\vee,\cO_X)\ar[r]& \sExt^1_{\cO_X}(f^*(E^\vee),\cO_X)\ar[r]& \sExt^2_{\cO_X}(L^{-1}f^*Q,\cO_X)\ar[r]&0. \end{tikzcd}\] The first term has dimension 0, so the sequence remains exact on taking global sections \[ egin{tikzcd}[sep=small] 0\ar[r]&H^0(\sExt^1_{\cO_X}((f^*E)^\vee,\cO_X))\ar[r]& H^0(\sExt^1_{\cO_X}(f^*(E^\vee),\cO_X))\ar[r]& H^0(\sExt^2_{\cO_X}(L^{-1}f^*Q,\cO_X))\ar[r]&0. \end{tikzcd}\] Combining this with Step 5, we have the claim. \end{proof} 
oindent\emph{Step 7.} Conclusion of proof. \vskip1em By the assumption on $E$ and \Cref{lem:vanishing} we have $Q
eq 0$. But then by the nonvanishing in Step 2 we have $0
eq \ell(H^0(\sExt^2_{\cO_X}(L^{-1}f^*Q,\cO_X)))$, so the claim follows from Step 6. \end{proof}  egin{proof}[Proof of \Cref{prop:blow-up to resolve}] Note it is equivalent to show $(f[\![u]\!]^*E)^\vee$ is locally free. Since $E^\vee$ is a reflexive $\mathcal O_{\mathcal T} [\![u]\!]$-module, we have \[ \sExt^i_{\mathcal O_{\mathcal T} [\![u]\!]}(E^\vee,\mathcal O_{\mathcal T} [\![u]\!])=0\] for $i>1$ by \Cref{lem:vanishing}. Moreover, $\sExt^1_{\mathcal O_{\mathcal T} [\![u]\!]}(E^\vee,\mathcal O_{\mathcal T} [\![u]\!])$ is supported at finitely many closed points, hence has finite length $\ell$. We proceed by induction on $\ell$, the $\ell=0$ case being trivial. Let $x \in \mathcal T$ be any point in the support, $\cO_{\mathcal T,x}$ the local ring of $\mathcal T$ at $x$ with maximal idea $ rak m_x$, and let $ rak n_x$ be the ideal generated by $ rak m_x$ in $\cO_{\mathcal T,x}[\![u]\!]$. Let \[ \pi:B	o \Spec\cO_{\mathcal T,x} \] be the blow-up at $ rak m_x$, and note that:  egin{itemize} \item the base-change $\pi[\![u]\!]:B[\![u]\!]	o \Spec (\cO_{\mathcal T,x} [\![u]\!])$ is the blow-up at $ rak n_x$, where $B[\![u]\!]$ denotes the scheme theoretic base change $B[\![u]\!] := B 	imes_{\Spec (\cO_{\mathcal T,x}} \Spec (\cO_{\mathcal T,x} [\![u]\!])$; \item the $p$-adic completions of the local rings of $B$ are identified with the local rings of the formal admissible blow-up \[ g:\mathcal T'	o \mathcal T \] of $\mathcal T$ at $x$. \end{itemize} In particular, for a closed point $x'$ of $\mathcal T'$ (which we also view as a closed point in $B [\![u]\!]$), the $p$-adic complete local ring \[ (\mathcal O_{\mathcal T'} [\![u]\!])_{x'} = \mathcal O_{\mathcal T', x'} [\![u]\!] \] is flat over $\cO_{B[\![u]\!],x'}$. Here $(\mathcal O_{\mathcal T'} [\![u]\!])_{x'}$ denotes the stalk of the sheaf $\mathcal O_{\mathcal T'} [\![u]\!]$ of the $p$-adic formal scheme $\mathcal T'$ at $x'$ According to \Cref{lem:strictly decreasing}, the length of $\sExt^1_{\mathcal O_{B[\![u]\!], x'}}((\pi[\![u]\!]^*E_x)^\vee,\cO_{B [\![u]\!], x'})$ is strictly smaller than \[ \ell_x := \sExt^1_{\mathcal O_{\mathcal T, x} [\![u]\!]}(E_x^\vee,\mathcal O_{\mathcal T, x} [\![u]\!]),\] so the same is true of $\sExt^1_{ (\mathcal O_{\mathcal T'} [\![u]\!])_{x'}}((g[\![u]\!]^*E_x)^\vee, (\mathcal O_{\mathcal T'} [\![u]\!])_{x'})$. Therefore, we know that \[ \ell  ig( \sExt^1_{ \mathcal O_{\mathcal T'} [\![u]\!]}((g[\![u]\!]^*E)^\vee,\mathcal O_{\mathcal T'} [\![u]\!])  ig) < \ell.\] By induction the proof is complete. \end{proof}

