0 \in \Z$ such that $P' \in V(\{a_l(z',\underline{t}) : l \leq m_0\}).$ This being true for every classical point $P'$, implies that $(\Dstar)^{a-1}	imes \sD^b = \cup_{m \in \Z} V(\{a_l(z',\underline{t}) : l \leq m\})$. By the Baire category theorem, this implies that there is an $m(i) \in \Z$ such that for $l < m(i)$, $a_l(z',\underline{t}) = 0$. In particular, $z_i^{-m(i)} f(\underline{z},\underline{t})$, extends analytically across the locus $z_i = 0$ as well. The function $\prod_{1\leq j \leq a} z_j^{-m(j)}f(\underline{z},\underline{t})$ thus extends analytically to the complement inside $\sD^{a+b}$ of the codimension 2 subvariety $\cup_{1 \leq r < s \leq a} V(z_r,z_s).$ Hence by the non-archimedean Hartog extension theorem \cite{bartenwerfer-hartog}, defines an analytic function on $\sD^{a+b}.$ This completes the proof. \end{proof}  egin{proof}[Proof of \Cref{extension-to-codim-1}] We may assume that $F = K$. Let $h^	imes : (\Dstar)^a 	imes \sD^b ightarrow X^\an$ be an analytic map. By \autoref{triviality-of-pic}, we may pick a trivialization $\phi : (h^	imes)^*(\mathscr{L}^\an) \xrightarrow{\sim} \cO_{(\Dstar)^a 	imes \sD^b}$ of the pullback line bundle $(h^	imes)^*(\mathscr{L}^\an)$. We let $\underline{z} := (z_1,\ldots,z_a)$ denote the coordinates on $(\Dstar)^a$ and $\underline{t} := (t_1,\ldots,t_b)$ the coordinates on $\sD^b.$ Let $f_r(\underline{z}, \underline{t}) := \phi(s_r) \in \cO((\Dstar)^a 	imes \sD^b)$. On classical points $(\underline{z},\underline{t}) \in (\Dstar)^a 	imes \sD^b$, the map $h^	imes : (\Dstar)^a 	imes \sD^b ightarrow X^\an \hookrightarrow \PP^{n,\an}_K$ is given in projective coordinates by $[f_0(\underline{z},\underline{t}) : \ldots : f_n(\underline{z},\underline{t})].$ For each $i \in \{1,\ldots,a\}$, and any finite extension $F$ of $K$ and an $F$-valued point $P' = (c_1,\ldots,\widehat{c_i},\ldots, c_a, \underline{	au}) \in (\Dstar)^{a-1}	imes \sD^b$, the analytic map $h^	imes_{P'} : \Dstar_F ightarrow \PP^{n,\an}_F$ given by